Germany, year zero
The 8th of May still reminds me of the year 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was truly a decisive moment in my life
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our small street, in the suburbs of west Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistance fighter, would be coming back from Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide like I did after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
The Nazis had left, and the occupying powers had not yet set up an administration.
We were looting the shops in the neighborhood. I still have some volumes of romantic poetry that I recovered from a bookstore.
I was sixteen years old. The occupying armies were committing all sorts of excesses.
It was difficult to obtain food.
My father was taken directly from his prison to the center of Berlin, and tasked with setting up - from scratch - the city's energy supply department.
For a certain period, there was neither electricity, nor transportation, nor organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans, it was a delicate question, even if for our family it was obviously a liberation in every sense of the word.
But for what purpose?
For what future?
“You must help”, my mother told me.
I therefore offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food products to a few distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back in school.
I had a special card for being a "victim of fascism," while others wore an Iron Cross obtained for late services to the army.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, almost all were mourning the loss of loved ones.
Yet, this stage did not last.
It's practically unbelievable, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle".
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and was accompanied by a new form of subjugation.
Concentration camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and detainees.
On the other hand, after a brief period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled reinforcement of autonomy.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, there were elections.
Democracy was not just an empty word, and it was based on German traditions.
Of course, not everything was benevolence on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and each one wanted to consolidate "their" part of Germany.
But there are still lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first is of an economic order, and related to the Marshall Plan.
It's perhaps regrettable, but democracy anchors itself more easily in a context of economic recovery.
To achieve this, one needs initiative above all, from individuals willing to put an end to a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, the father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with a starting capital.
This is why American support through the Marshall Plan is so important.
The European Union has also helped former communist countries and continues to accompany them on their path.
The other lesson, of a moral order, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany did not start its long journey by focusing on the past.
In fact, many have described the Adenauer years after 1949 as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi personalities remained in their positions.
In a way, the country was ignoring its past to move forward towards the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and a political democracy, Germany faced its past, with a lot of success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other devastated countries are therefore confusing.
Yet, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first novelty, then an attempt to come to terms with the past.
Ultimately, it is a better method.
In Europe, May 8, 2005, is an occasion to look at the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn towards the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and therefore filled with hope.
